commit.message:
Add `format_as`, `push_to_huggingface`, & `from_huggingface` in `FeedbackDataset` (#2949)

# Description

This PR adds some methods to the `rg.FeedbackDataset` as follows:

* `format_as` to format the records of the existing dataset as
🤗`datasets` format (i.e. `datasets.Dataset`) to be extended to support
other formats like `pandas` or `numpy`
* `push_to_huggingface` to push the existing records and dataset
configuration to the HuggingFace Hub (including an auto-generated
dataset card! 🎉)
* `from_huggingface` is a classmethod to load a `rg.FeedbackDataset`
from the HuggingFace Hub, pulling the dataset itself (records and
annotations) and the configuration (guidelines, fields, and questions)

Closes #2765

**Type of change**

commit.message:
List all the `FeedbackDataset` responses not just the current user's (#2943)

# Description

As recently spotted by @nataliaElv, we were just listing the current
dataset records with their annotations, instead of all the available
record annotations, as we were sending the request to `GET
/api/v1/me/datasets/{id}/records` instead to `GET
/api/v1/datasets/{id}/records`, so removing the prefix `/me` solves this
issue.

Kudos to @nataliaElv 🎉

commit.message:
Add new `FeedbackDataset` class using `/api/v1` endpoints (#2827)

## Description

This PR addresses the creation of a new `FeedbackDataset` class to
handle the new datasets provided in Argilla. These datasets define some
fields and questions for every dataset. The fields are the inputs, while
the questions are the "annotations" which in this case correspond to
questions over the fields that can either be numerical or textual, so
that the annotator has to answer those questions in order to label the
data.

This PR closes #2758, and #2764

**Type of change**

- [X] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality)

**How Has This Been Tested**

- [X] Included unit tests for `/api/v1/datasets` endpoint wrappers
- [X] Included unit tests for `rg.FeedbackDataset` class and any other
related method/function

**Checklist**

- [X] I have merged the original branch into my forked branch
- [X] I added relevant documentation
- [X] follows the style guidelines of this project
- [X] I did a self-review of my code
- [X] I made corresponding changes to the documentation
- [ ] My changes generate no new warnings
- [X] I have added tests that prove my fix is effective or that my
feature works
- [ ] I have added relevant notes to the CHANGELOG.md file (See
https://keepachangelog.com/)

## Example

```python
import argilla as rg

rg.init(
    api_url="<ARGILLA_URL_GOES_HERE>",
    api_key="<ARGILLA_API_KEY_GOES_HERE>",
)

dataset = rg.FeedbackDataset(
  guidelines="...",
  fields=[
    rg.TextField(name="prompt", required=True),
    rg.TextField(name="context", required=False),
    rg.TextField(name="completion", required=True),
  ],
  questions=[
    rg.RatingQuestion(name="prompt-quality", title="Assess the quality of the prompt", required=True),
    rg.TextQuestion(name="prompt-edit", title="Edit the prompt if applicable", required=False),
  ]
)

dataset.add_records(records=[
  rg.FeedbackRecord(
    fields={"prompt": ..., "context": ..., "completion": ...}
  ),
])
print(dataset.records[0])
dataset.push_to_argilla(name="my-dataset", workspace="my-workspace")
```

---------

Co-authored-by: Francisco Aranda <francis@argilla.io>

Add new `FeedbackDataset` class using `/api/v1` endpoints (#2827)

## Description

This PR addresses the creation of a new `FeedbackDataset` class to
handle the new datasets provided in Argilla. These datasets define some
fields and questions for every dataset. The fields are the inputs, while
the questions are the "annotations" which in this case correspond to
questions over the fields that can either be numerical or textual, so
that the annotator has to answer those questions in order to label the
data.

This PR closes #2758, and #2764

**Type of change**

- [X] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality)

**How Has This Been Tested**

- [X] Included unit tests for `/api/v1/datasets` endpoint wrappers
- [X] Included unit tests for `rg.FeedbackDataset` class and any other
related method/function

**Checklist**

- [X] I have merged the original branch into my forked branch
- [X] I added relevant documentation
- [X] follows the style guidelines of this project
- [X] I did a self-review of my code
- [X] I made corresponding changes to the documentation
- [ ] My changes generate no new warnings
- [X] I have added tests that prove my fix is effective or that my
feature works
- [ ] I have added relevant notes to the CHANGELOG.md file (See
https://keepachangelog.com/)

## Example

```python
import argilla as rg

rg.init(
    api_url="<ARGILLA_URL_GOES_HERE>",
    api_key="<ARGILLA_API_KEY_GOES_HERE>",
)

dataset = rg.FeedbackDataset(
  guidelines="...",
  fields=[
    rg.TextField(name="prompt", required=True),
    rg.TextField(name="context", required=False),
    rg.TextField(name="completion", required=True),
  ],
  questions=[
    rg.RatingQuestion(name="prompt-quality", title="Assess the quality of the prompt", required=True),
    rg.TextQuestion(name="prompt-edit", title="Edit the prompt if applicable", required=False),
  ]
)

dataset.add_records(records=[
  rg.FeedbackRecord(
    fields={"prompt": ..., "context": ..., "completion": ...}
  ),
])
print(dataset.records[0])
dataset.push_to_argilla(name="my-dataset", workspace="my-workspace")
```

commit.message:
Increase `codecov` threshold to avoid status checks from failing due to it (#2934)

# Description

Tiny PR to update the `.codecov.yml` configuration file to relax the
restrictions from `codecov` in the current status checks, since it's
making a lot of status checks in PRs fail due to a super small code
coverage change e.g. 0.1

So on, the new configuration file uses `target: auto` to compare the
coverage of the current code with the previous base commit used to
calculate the diff, and `threshold: 2%` to allow a 2 percent difference
with respect to the base commit coverage.

**Type of change**

- [X] Improvement (change adding some improvement to an existing
functionality)

Using an already setup httpx client in sdk modules (#2919)

# Description

Since the new SDK modules are creating a new httpx client on each
request, some problems related to connection performance can be raised.
In the [official docs](https://www.python-httpx.org/advanced/) you can
read:

> When you make requests using the top-level API as documented in the
[Quickstart](https://www.python-httpx.org/quickstart/) guide, HTTPX has
to establish a new connection for every single request (connections are
not reused). As the number of requests to a host increases, this quickly
becomes inefficient.
> 
> On the other hand, a Client instance uses [HTTP connection
pooling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_persistent_connection). This
means that when you make several requests to the same host, the Client
will reuse the underlying TCP connection, instead of recreating one for
every single request.

In order to better use the httpx client, this PR changes the `sdk`
module to reuse the already set up httpx client in the
`AuthenticatedClient` instance.

By using this client, you don't need to pass header or base URL
configuration on each request, since is setup on client initialization.

commit.message:
fix: `POST /api/v1/datasets` doesn't handle non-existing workspace ids (#2754)

# Description

I've updated the `POST /api/v1/datasets` endpoint to check if the
`workspace_id` provided in the `body` of the request exists. If there is
no `workspace` object associated to the provided id, the endpoint will
return `404 Not Found`. I've also added a new unit test to cover this
case.

Closes #2753 

**Type of change**

(Please delete options that are not relevant. Remember to title the PR
according to the type of change)

- [x] Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would cause existing
functionality to not work as expected)
- [ ] Refactor (change restructuring the codebase without changing
functionality)
- [x] Improvement (change adding some improvement to an existing
functionality)
- [ ] Documentation update

**How Has This Been Tested**

- Manually:
- I tried to create a dataset using the `POST /api/v1/datasets` endpoint
and providing a non-existing `workspace_id`. I got `404`. No new rows
were added to the DB.
- Unit Test

commit.message:
Admin users can create records with responses for several users (#2906)

# Description

WARNING !!! This PR changes the records creation endpoint.

Instead of passing a single response, now the endpoint accepts a list of
user responses. This allows admins to restore a backup of the dataset.

@alvarobartt Once this PR is merged in the feature branch, you should
adapt the add_records method to accept a list of users' responses. See
[here](https://github.com/argilla-io/argilla/blob/6fe3d3c2f9c958435e660d192e081203453bf1cb/src/argilla/server/schemas/v1/datasets.py#L228)
for the schema definition.

Closes #2903
